Nieuwezijds Voorburgwal, Amsterdam. Summer 1942. SD agents check the identity card of Jewish citizens on the Nieuwezijdse Voorburgwal. At the beginning of January 1941, the compulsory registration of Jews with the population register was proclaimed. Proof of registration should always be carried with you. In order to determine whether someone was Jewish, it was decided in the summer of 1941 that a large J had to be placed in two places on the identity card of so-called 'Volljuden'. From that moment on, Jews were easy to distinguish from non-Jews at street checks. Time: summer 1942

Amsterdam, Polderweg. May 25, 1943. 500 Jews respond to the German appeal ('Convocation') and report to leave for camp Westerbork. They wait for hours for the special train that will transport them from Muiderpoort Station to Westerbork. Of the 7,000 Jews who had to report to the Polderweg that day for deportation to Westerbork, only 500 appeared that day, much to the irritation of the Germans. Jewish students of the school on the Cliffordstraat, Amsterdam West. Only one class with 10 students. From August 1941 there had to be schools for exclusively Jewish pupils and teachers. There were of course also Jewish families living outside the 'Jewish neighbourhoods'; with about a hundred Jewish 'public' children, especially in West, according to the report from July '41. The municipality opened one school for these children, who lived very widely, in the Staatsliedenbuurt, at number 36 Cliffordstraat, in a school building that was no longer in use. It was quite eccentric from the other western neighborhoods of the city. At the end of September 1941, when that Jewish school no. 14 opened, only 56 children showed up. The Education Department had probably assumed a larger turnout, three classes had been formed with two teachers plus the head Moses Goubitz, he came from the Corantijnschool at Surinameplein. Given the enormous distances that some children would have to walk on foot every day, it is likely that many parents kept their children at home from September 1941 onwards. Education was compulsory, also for the Jewish children, but the supervision of this failed. Abel Herzberg in his Chronicle of the Persecution of the Jews (p242): 'Sometimes a child had to walk from home to school for an hour or more. Trams and bicycles were, after all, prohibited. Sometimes a Jewish Council pushcart would collect the heavy school bags from the houses. When it was handed over to the Education Office of the Jewish Council in December 1942, of course, this small school did not escape the austerity reorganization. At that time there were only 25 pupils and it did not require 3 teachers; it became a one-class school, which, despite attempts to find accommodation elsewhere, remained located in the school building on Cliffordstraat; the rest of the building was closed off. That lasted until the end of May 1943; West was also not spared by the occupying forces during the large raids, so that in the last week of May hardly any children showed up. The education board also closed this school on May 31; headmaster Mozes Goubitz had already been succeeded by Gerrit van Praag and he went into hiding immediately in those days. Master Jakob Druijf, who lived in West and was out of work when school No. 1 on the Oude Schans was closed, took the handful of children that were still there under his care, at his home in the Jan van Galenstraat.

After the first transports in the summer of 1942, fewer and fewer people heeded the German call to report before leaving for Westerbork. The Amsterdam police collected the Jews from home and brought them to the Hollandsche Schouwburg. The Jewish Council had made a number of facilities in the theatre, but these turned out to be far from sufficient to accommodate three to four hundred people reasonably. Sometimes the detainees stayed there only for a day, but the stay could also last a week. In the dark of the night the Jews left for Westerbork.

Employees of the department Help for Departures with luggage at the Oude Schans 74. In the Oude Schans building 72 - 76, the sub-departments of 'Help for Departures' were located: Clothes supply, Camp articles, a sewing workshop and the 'Baggage Department' where the luggage sent to Westerbork, among others. In November 1942, 416 employees worked here. Working for the Jewish Council resulted in a 'Sperre'. When the deportation of Jews started in 1942, there were many applications for work in this department.
specific_location: The Baggage Department, The Jewish Council, Amsterdam

research_and_notes: A Jewish nurse has volunteered to report to the sports complex on Olympiaplein in Amsterdam. Her elderly patients had been arrested earlier that day. She chose to stay with them and was taken to Westerbork together with her patients. The woman did not survive the war. Olympiaplein, June 20, 1943.

Jewish children receive music lessons in a room in the Nieuwe Kerkstraat. pg. VII. The Out-of-School Youth Care (BJZ) was one of the dozens of departments of the Jewish Council. For Jewish children, the BJZ was a welcome distraction from the worries of everyday life. In the few available and hardly usable premises, the BJZ tried to create a relaxed atmosphere. Jewish youth leaders kept the children busy with activities such as crafts, music, folk dancing and Jewish history. There was also a lot of sports. This met a clear need because Jewish children were not allowed to be members of sports and other recreational associations. This photo comes from a small photo album with a total of 36 photos. The photographer, who has remained anonymous, prefaces his work with a handwritten introduction: ' Flashes from the work of the Out-of-School Youth Care. This album doesn't want to show more - it can't show more - because only flashes are possible of the ever-changing aspects that the care for young people shows outside school hours.'
specific_location: After-school Youth Care, The Jewish Council, Amsterdam
